data.enText: a person who is the next most important person below a business manager, a head of a school, a political leader, etc. and who does the person's job when he or she is away

data.chText: 我在经理回来之前代行他的职务。
data.enText: I'm acting as deputy till the manager returns.
the deputy head of a school
the name for a member of parliament in some countries

data.chText: （美国协助地方治安官办案的）警官
data.enText: (in the US) a police officer who helps the sheriff of an area

means: (美国协助地方治安官办案的)警官

ex.chText: 政府派了10位代表前往中国。
ex.enText: The government has sent ten delegates to China.

ex.chText: 保守党已经派出代表参加大会。
ex.enText: The Conservatives have sent their delegates to the conference.

synonyms.bx: 通常由选举产生或由政府、党派等指派，主要为某一群体阐述意见、进行投票选举、作决策等。

ex.chText: 我不在时，我弟弟将代理我的工作。
ex.enText: My brother will act as a deputy for me while I am away.

ex.chText: 这个公司的董事长派一名副手出席了会议。
ex.enText: The president of the company appointed a deputy to attend the meeting.

synonyms.bx: 指被上级授权具体行事、职位仅居于其下的人。

ex.chText: 他是中国驻联合国的常驻代表。
ex.enText: He is the permanent representative/delegate of China to the UN.
He once had worked as a union representative/delegate.

synonyms.bx: 通常指被推选或者被任命的代表，其职务有时是较长期的，常可与 delegate 换用。

tr: an assistant with power to act when his superior is absent
someone authorized to exercise the powers of sheriff in emergencies
a person appointed to represent or act on behalf of others
a member of the lower chamber of a legislative assembly (such as in France)

value.def: A deputy is the second most important person in an organization such as a business or government department. Someone's deputy often acts on their behalf when they are not there.

example.ex: ...Jack Lang, France's minister for culture, and his deputy, Catherine Tasca.
example.tran: 法国文化部长杰克·朗和他的副部长凯瑟琳·塔斯卡
学院副院长弗拉基米尔·库德里亚夫采夫

value.def: In some parliaments or law-making bodies, the elected members are called deputies .

example.ex: The president appealed to deputies to approve the plan quickly.
example.tran: 总统呼吁议员尽快通过这一方案。
